04818nam a2200565Ia 9781438466958DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20172017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814384669587 a10.1515/97814384669582doi  a(DE-B1597)683597  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE165 7aHIS0360402bisacsh04a328.73/092aB2231 aSandford, Ann, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReluctant Reformer :bNathan Sanford in the Era of the Early Republic /cAnn Sandford. 1aAlbany : bSUNY Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (216 p.) :bTotal Illustrations: 12  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aExcelsior Editions00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tRural Heritage of an Ambitious Son, 1750–1795 -- tLegal Training and Law Practice, 1795–1806 -- tUnited States Attorney for New York, 1803–1815 -- tState Politician and Legislator, 1800–1815 -- tWealth and Charges of Corruption, 1800–1820 -- tUnited States Senator and the Politics of Commerce, 1815–1821 -- tSenate Politics and Reform, 1815–1821 -- t“Here there is but one estate—the people,” 1821 -- tThe Suffrage Debate, 1821 -- tChancellor, 1823–1826 -- tCandidate and Senator, 1824–1831 -- tRetirement, 1831–1838 -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSet in the tumultuous decades of post-revolutionary America, Reluctant Reformer brings to light the long neglected New York lawyer-politician, Nathan Sanford. As a lawyer, Sanford contributed to modern property law. In the United States Senate, he dealt with central banking, struggled against slavery, and supported popular voting for presidential electors. He was a major designer of the program to rationalize the nation's currency. Against a backdrop of European wars and the War of 1812, he capitalized on opportunities for upward social mobility in a period of nation-building and commercial expansion. At the New York State Constitutional Convention of 1821, he fought for universal manhood suffrage.Educated in history and government at Clinton Academy on Long Island and at Yale, and a student at the Litchfield School of Law, Sanford rose quickly to prominence as the federal attorney appointed by President Jefferson to serve all of New York State. Fueled by ambition, he navigated a career among Republican factional leaders—DeWitt Clinton, Aaron Burr, and Martin Van Buren—first in New York City, and then in the state and the nation. In 1824, he ran for vice president on the ticket with Henry Clay. Attuned to his familial ties to eastern Long Island but beyond the bounds of the rural community of his youth, Sanford faced decisions about whom to trust with a militia's gun and a citizen's vote. He could shift from his principles toward political compromise, as in restricting black male suffrage and in the removal of Indians from their ancestral lands.In this book, Sanford is revealed as a wealth-seeking lawyer and officeholder who contributed to the expansion of democratic rights and responsive government in the Early Republic. In doing so, he proved to be a reluctant reformer who deserves a place in our public memory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aLawyerszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 0aLegislatorszUnited StatesvBiography. 4aAmerican Studies : Indigenous Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aNew York/Regional : New York State Government. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2017z978311149102840uhttps://